04095nam a22006735i 9780820705071DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808207050717 a10.1515/97808207050712doi  a(DE-B1597)612378  a(OCoLC)1322124843  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPR3069.R44bB46 2009 7aLIT0190002bisacsh04a822.3/32221 aBenson, Sean, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aShakespearean Resurrection :bThe Art of Almost Raising the Dead /cSean Benson. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (229 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMedieval & Renaissance Literary Studies00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION Shakespeare’s Art of Almost Raising the Dead -- tONE The Comedies: Recognition and Quasi Resurrection -- tTWO Failed Resurrections in Romeo and Juliet and Othello -- tTHREE Cordelia’s Quasi Resurrection and Shakespearean Revision -- tFOUR The Limits of Stage Resurrection in Pericles and Cymbeline -- tFIVE Raising the Dead in The Winter’s Tale and The Tempest -- tAPPENDIX Mock Resurrections -- tNOTES -- tWORKS CITED -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis engaging book demonstrates Shakespeare’s abiding interest in the theatrical potential of the Christian resurrection from the dead. In fourteen of Shakespeare’s plays, characters who have been lost, sometimes for years, suddenly reappear seemingly returning from the dead. In the classical recognition scene, such moments are explained away in naturalistic terms a character was lost at sea but survived, or abducted and escaped, and so on. Shakespeare never invalidates such explanations, but in his manipulation of classical conventions he parallels these moments with the recognition scenes from the Gospels, repeatedly evoking Christ’s resurrection from the dead.Benson’s close study of the plays, as well as the classical and biblical sources that Shakespeare fuses into his recognition scenes, clearly elucidates the ways in which the playwright explored his abiding interest in the human desire to transcend death and to live reunited and reconciled with others. In his manipulation of resurrection imagery, Shakespeare conflates the material with the immaterial, the religious with the secular, and the sacred with the profane.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aDead in literature. 0aResurrection in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780820705071?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780820705071423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780820705071/original  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK